{"Body": "<p><span style=\"font-size: small;\">On the eve of the November 3rd student march, UCD Students' Union released the results of a poll of 1000 randomly-chosen Irish adults commissioned to investigate attitudes to funding of the third-level sector in Ireland. The results showed that 77% of all adults believe that free fees should remain in place, while 90% of 18-24 year olds expressed that opinion.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Respondents ranked job creation as the highest priority for economic recovery, with third-level education coming second.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><span style=\"font-size: 15px;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">TCDSU President Nikolai Trigoub-Rotnem said of the survey \"This shows that the Irish people are convinced that there can be no recovery without support for third-level education. My question to TDs is 'Why aren't you listening?' They're planning to slash student support and college funding because they think students are a soft target. Well this just shows how out of touch they are with voters, and if the government doesn't cap the reg fee and halt grant cuts on December 7th, then they'll see what happens when you ignore voters.\"</span></span></span></strong></span></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 15px; \"><strong><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The survey is released as students prepare to take to the streets in protest against the proposed cuts to the third level sector in the upcoming budget. The results will galvanise supporters of the march who have worried in recent days that public opinion might turn against the march if it fails to arouse sufficient sympathy&nbsp;</span></span></span></strong></span></p>", "Imageurl": "<p><span style=\"font-size: small;\">On the eve of the November 3rd student march, UCD Students' Union released the results of a poll of 1000 randomly-chosen Irish adults commissioned to investigate attitudes to funding of the third-level sector in Ireland. The results showed that 77% of all adults believe that free fees should remain in place, while 90% of 18-24 year olds expressed that opinion.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Respondents ranked job creation as the highest priority for economic recovery, with third-level education coming second.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><span style=\"font-size: 15px;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">TCDSU President Nikolai Trigoub-Rotnem said of the survey \"This shows that the Irish people are convinced that there can be no recovery without support for third-level education. My question to TDs is 'Why aren't you listening?' They're planning to slash student support and college funding because they think students are a soft target. Well this just shows how out of touch they are with voters, and if the government doesn't cap the reg fee and halt grant cuts on December 7th, then they'll see what happens when you ignore voters.\"</span></span></span></strong></span></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 15px; \"><strong><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The survey is released as students prepare to take to the streets in protest against the proposed cuts to the third level sector in the upcoming budget. The results will galvanise supporters of the march who have worried in recent days that public opinion might turn against the march if it fails to arouse sufficient sympathy&nbsp;</span></span></span></strong></span></p>", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "789", "Heading": "77% of adults want free fees - Red C Poll"}